{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7d474435-4cf6-4fbe-b37f-cf7da405229c","content":"This is a known breaking change. Android 15 (API 35) enforces **edge-to-edge** rendering, which ignores the old `adjustResize` mode. In .NET 10 (targeting API 35+), you need to react to **WindowInsets** instead.\n\nThe fix is to listen for IME (keyboard) insets on Android and adjust your page's bottom padding. Here's how:\n\n**1. `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`** — register an insets listener:\n\n```csharp\nusing Android.OS;\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\npublic class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity\n{\n    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n    {\n        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n        if (Window?.DecorView is { } decor)\n        {\n            var content = decor.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;\n            ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(content, new ImeInsetsListener());\n        }\n    }\n\n    sealed class ImeInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener\n    {\n        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(\n            Android.Views.View view, WindowInsetsCompat insets)\n        {\n            var ime  = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());\n            var bars = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());\n\n            int bottom = Math.Max(ime.Bottom, bars.Bottom);\n            view.SetPadding(bars.Left, bars.Top, bars.Right, bottom);\n\n            return WindowInsetsCompat.Consumed;\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**2. Your XAML** stays straightforward — just use a `Grid` with the input bar at the bottom:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage>\n  <Grid RowDefinitions=\"*, Auto\">\n    <CollectionView Grid.Row=\"0\" ItemsSource=\"{Binding Messages}\"\n                    ItemsUpdatingScrollMode=\"KeepLastItemInView\" />\n    <Grid Grid.Row=\"1\" ColumnDefinitions=\"*, Auto\" Padding=\"8\">\n      <Entry Placeholder=\"Type a message...\" />\n      <Button Grid.Column=\"1\" Text=\"Send\" />\n    </Grid>\n  </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**Why this works:** `WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()` reports the keyboard height. The listener applies that as bottom padding on the content view, pushing your entire page layout (including the input bar) above the keyboard — the same effect `adjustResize` used to give you, but through the modern insets API.\n\n**iOS** doesn't need this — MAUI already handles keyboard avoidance there via `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b727d46c-b92d-432a-9cf0-49edda63367b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI issue with keyboard handling in .NET 10. This is a known breaking change — `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated/removed because Android itself deprecated the `adjustResize` soft input mode in favor of the new edge-to-edge / WindowInsets API.\n\nLet me provide a concise, accurate answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI evolution.\n\nIn .NET 10 (and starting with Android 15 / API 35), `adjustResize` is no longer honored when targeting edge-to-edge. The recommended approach is to use the new `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` or handle `WindowInsets` properly.\n\n\nSo the evolution is clear: .NET 9 had `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` mapping to Android's `adjustResize`, but Android deprecated that in favor of edge-to-edge insets starting with Android 15. In .NET 10, the solution is to leverage `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` for automatic keyboard scroll behavior or manually manage the edge-to-edge insets. In .NET 10 on Android 15+, edge-to-edge is enforced and `adjustResize` gets ignored, so I need to work with the `WindowInsets` API instead. The practical solutions are using `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` which handles scrolling automatically, listening to keyboard insets and adjusting padding manually, or structuring the layout with a Grid so content responds properly.\n\nFor a chat screen, I can set up a listener in the Android platform code to detect IME insets and adjust the view's padding accordingly. But actually, the simplest approach for MAUI is to use the new edge-to-edge insets API on Android—I'd set up a window insets callback in MainActivity that captures the IME height and applies it to the layout.\n\nBut actually, there's likely a simpler approach in recent MAUI versions. In .NET 9 and 10, keyboard handling improved significantly, especially with edge-to-edge becoming the default on Android 15+. The easiest fix is usually just making sure the page content properly respects the safe area.\n\nFor a chat UI specifically, I want the input bar at the bottom to shift up when the keyboard appears. I can structure this with a grid where the message list takes up available space and the input controls sit below, then handle the keyboard insets on Android to ensure proper padding and scrolling behavior.","outputTokens":2205,"requestId":"B7D7:5276A:18E07D:205389:69FFDA8E"},"id":"1b4aa30b-8395-4b08-92e6-87f98685a369","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:09:13.962Z","parentId":"6a2847f9-ae40-4bd9-aaa8-5f796bbe0a1e"}
